{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477784"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.03,0.86,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7408"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43602"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"2918"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44221"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of puffy eyes and swollen legs. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. He has periorbital and peripheral oedema. His urine dipstick shows 3+ protein.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin 28 g/L (35-50)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine 45 \u00b5mol/L (20-60)\u003Cbr /\u003ECholesterol 6.8 mmol/L (2.8-4.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA renal biopsy confirms focal segmental glomerulosclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cyclophosphamide","Cyclosporine","Oral prednisolone","Rituximab","Mycophenolate mofetil"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with nephrotic syndrome, characterised by oedema, proteinuria, hypoalbuminaemia, and hypercholesterolaemia. The renal biopsy confirms focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS), which accounts for approximately 10-20% of cases of nephrotic syndrome in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for FSGS in children. The typical regimen involves daily prednisolone at 2 mg/kg/day (maximum 60 mg) for 4-8 weeks, followed by alternate-day therapy if there is a response. Response to steroids is the most important prognostic factor in childhood FSGS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclosporine\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved as second-line therapy for steroid-resistant cases. While effective, it requires careful monitoring of drug levels and renal function, and has significant side effects including nephrotoxicity and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclophosphamide\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in steroid-resistant cases, but its use is limited by significant side effects including bone marrow suppression and increased risk of infections. It is not appropriate as first-line therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycophenolate mofetil\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used as a steroid-sparing agent in children who have responded to initial steroid therapy but become steroid-dependent. It would not be appropriate as initial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERituximab\u003C/strong\u003E is generally reserved for cases that have failed multiple other therapies. Its role in primary FSGS is still being evaluated, and it would not be appropriate as first-line treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular monitoring of proteinuria (using urine protein/creatinine ratio), renal function, and complications of nephrotic syndrome is essential. Supportive care including dietary sodium restriction and management of oedema with diuretics may also be required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["First-line treatment for focal segmental glomerulosclerosis in children is oral prednisolone for 4-8 weeks.","Calcineurin inhibitors are second-line therapy for steroid-resistant focal segmental glomerulosclerosis.","Regular monitoring of proteinuria is essential to assess treatment response in focal segmental glomerulosclerosis."],"references":["Gipson DS, Gibson K, Gipson PE, Watkins S, Moxey-Mims M. Therapeutic approach to FSGS in children. Pediatr Nephrol. 2007 Jan;22(1):28-36. doi: 10.1007/s00467-006-0310-4. Epub 2006 Nov 16. PMID: 17109140; PMCID: PMC1784542."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43602"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43602"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T14:23:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T14:24:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7408"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58143"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":f